{"staticQueryHashes":[],"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-boattemplate-jsx","path":"/boat/1990","result":{"pageContext":{"pathSlug":"/boat/1990","home":"/","absolute":"https://oga.org.uk","boat":{"id":"0824a7cb-dcf4-4093-8870-93b4adc6aaa7","name":"Patience","previous_names":null,"year":1993,"year_is_approximate":false,"place_built":"Poole","home_port":"Poole","home_country":"GBR","ssr":null,"sail_number":null,"nhsr":null,"nsbr":null,"oga_no":1990,"fishing_number":null,"callsign":"","mssi":null,"full_description":"<p>Patience was built by shipwright Peter Atkins in Poole. He was a keen Old Gaffer racing man, who having sailed several types of gaffer decided he could design and build one better and faster. It took him 5 years and there is an album of photographs that records the whole process. Time was not of the essence and great care was given to the constructin and the detai work.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The boat was built using West Epoxy System and BS 1088 marine ply, with teak laid decks and teak and mahogany exterior fit out. The shape is very conventional with a long keel, straight stem, good freeboard and multichine. She has&nbsp; a generous interior volume. She is fairly full mid-ships producing ample buoyancy so she stands up to her canvas.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The chines land on a full length internal stringer and there are a number of heavy laminated rig frames which span across the centre-line. The bulkheads at the forward and after ends of the saloon are structural and epoxy bonded to the skin.</p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\">Carved hanging knees either side of the doorway frame posts in the forward bulkhead and full ring frames in way all take the compression of the deck stepped mast. Laminated hanging knees on the cabin coamings in the main cabin and in the fore cabin in way of the forward end of the coach-roof all serve to stiffen that structure.</font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\">She has a very sweet sheer rising gently aft emphasised by varnished rubbing strakes top and bottom of the wide sheer strake. The forward and after ends of the sheer strake have &quot;badges&quot; carved and picked out in paint against the varnish. The fore foot is very square giving her grip in the water and directional stability and the transom has a delicate tumble-home to the upper edges. The transom-hung rudder has a step in it allowing someone in the water to climb back aboard.</font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\">Heavy galvanised steel centre-plate incorporated into the companionway step and stowed in the raised position within the depth of the wood keel. The plate is raised by a lanyard through a stainless steel pipe by the main sheet support. Several cast iron ballast blocks are secured in the bilge across the centre-line.</font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\">A relatively large, sealed cock-pit gives space for 4 crew. The cabin entrance with sliding hatch and wash-boards has a sill at seat level. The deck is swept-laid in teak over a ply sub deck. The rig is set up with halyards led aft along the coach-roof deck through clutches to a top-action Harken 9 winch each side of the entrance hatch. Jib and staysail sheets are lead through lead blocks on deck tracks to jammers.</font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\">Accommodation.- 3 berths</font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\">Fore cabin with single berth to stbd. The feet of the berth reach forward under the deck chain well.</font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\">Saloon cabin. Port and starboard settee berths. Shaped, buttoned cushions. Shaped bunk boards. Exposed varnished yacht sides.</font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\">Fold down chart desk against the after bulkhead to stbd. A 2-bruner Origo spirit stove mounted on rails on the bulkhead over the end of the port berth slides across to the centre-line against the companionway steps for use.</font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\">Since purchase in 2015 works carried out include</font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\">1) Hull repainted</font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\">2) New mast and spars (Freelands)</font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\">3) New standing and running rigging</font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\">4) Sails refurbished and set up for Wykeham Martin</font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\"><font face=\"Helvetica\" size=\"2\">5) Wykeham Martin on jib and staysail</font></font></p>","image_key":"3LpNhN","uk_part1":null,"spar_material":"wood","rig_type":"Cutter","construction_material":"plywood","construction_method":"unknown","construction_details":"West System Marine Ply","draft":0.7864,"generic_type":"Yacht","handicap_data":{"beam":2.286027798098025,"main":{"foot":3.6576444769568397,"head":3.3528407705437697,"luff":3.6576444769568397},"thcf":0.870332415,"draft":0.8138258961228968,"length_over_all":6.958668617410387,"fore_triangle_base":3.429041697147037,"length_on_waterline":6.4770787612777365,"fore_triangle_height":5.6388685686417945},"hull_form":"long keel deep forefoot","keel_laid":null,"launched":null,"length_on_deck":6.9586,"mainsail_type":"gaff","short_description":"<p>23' gaff cutter designed and built by first owner Peter Atkins of Poole and launched in 1993.</p>","updated_at":"2021-05-13T21:22:52.10902+00:00","website":"","beam":2.3622,"air_draft":null,"reference":null,"builder":"ace7bd86-4eec-4ec5-8695-ef66dfb468f2","designer":"b8a2eff0-225e-40f4-9335-43d1055c0735","design_class":null,"constructionMaterialByConstructionMaterial":{"name":"plywood"},"constructionMethodByConstructionMethod":{"name":"unknown"},"designClassByDesignClass":null,"designerByDesigner":{"name":"P. Atkins"},"rigTypeByRigType":{"name":"Cutter"},"genericTypeByGenericType":{"name":"Yacht"},"builderByBuilder":{"name":"P. Atkins","notes":null},"for_sale_state":{"text":"for_sale"},"for_sales":[{"asking_price":14500,"flexibility":null,"offered":null,"price_flexibility":null,"reduced":null,"sales_text":"<p >Patience is a boat which is based on the Mk 1 Crabber, very nicely put together and has proved to be faster.</span></p> <table > <tr > <td width=125 valign=bottom > <p ><span >Length on deck</span></p> </td> <td width=125 valign=bottom ><p ><span >23’</span></p> </td> </tr> <tr > <td width=125 border-top:none; height:16.1pt;mso-height-rule:> <p ><span >Beam</span></p> </td> <td width=125 height:16.1pt;mso-height-rule:> <p ><span >7’8”</span></p> </td> </tr> <tr style='mso-yfti-irow:2;height:16.1pt;mso-height-rule:> <td width=125 border-top:none; height:16.1pt;mso-height-rule:> <p ><span >Draft plate up</span></p> </td> <td width=125 height:16.1pt;mso-height-rule:> <p ><span >2’8”</span></p> </td> </tr> <tr style='mso-yfti-irow:3;mso-yfti-lastrow:yes;h > <td width=125 border-top:none; h> <p ><span >Draft plate down</span></p> </td> <td width=125 h> <p ><span >4’8”</span></p> </td> </tr> </table> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >Mercury 5hp Sail Drive (less than 20 hrs use) in outboard well. </span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >NASA LED tricolour/anchor light on mast,</span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >Clipper duet log/depth sounder</span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >Currently ashore at Ridge Wharf Yacht Centre. Wareham</span></p> <p ><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >She was built by shipwright Peter Atkins from Poole, for himself. He was a keen Old Gaffer race man who having sailed several of the type believed that he could design and build a better and faster boat. Completed in 1993 it took him 5 years and an album of photos records the whole process.  Time was not of the essence and great care was given to the construction and the detail work. </span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >The boat is built using the West Epoxy System and BS 1088 marine ply, with teak laid deck and teak and mahogany exterior fit-out.  The shape is very conventional – a long keel, straight stem, good freeboard and multi-chine with a fairly full mid-ships section producing ample buoyancy so that she stands up to her rig, with a generous interior volume.</span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >The chines land on a full-length internal stringer and there are a number of heavy laminated rig frames which span across the centre-line. The bulkheads at the forward and after end of the saloon are structural and epoxy bonded to the skin. Carved hanging knees either side of the doorway frame posts in the forward bulkhead and full ring frames in way all take the compression of the deck stepped mast. Laminated hanging knees on the cabin coamings in the main cabin and in the fore cabin in way of the forward end of the coach-roof all serve to stiffen that structure.</span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;vertical-align: baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >She has a very sweet sheer rising gently aft emphasised by rubbing strakes top and bottom of the wide sheer strake. The forward and after ends of the sheer strake have carved “badges”. The fore foot is very square giving her grip in the water and directional stability and the transom has a delicate tumble-home to the upper edges. The transom-hung rudder has a step in it allowing someone in the water to climb back aboard.</span><span style='mso-no-proof:yes'> </span><span ></span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >Heavy galvanised steel centre-plate incorporated into the companionway step and stowed in the raised position within the depth of the wood keel. The plate is raised by a lanyard through a stainless-steel pipe by the main sheet support. </span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >A relatively large, sealed cock-pit gives space for 4 crew. Large sealed down hatches in the cock-pit sole lift to give generous access to the area below. The seats are artistically shaped opening to access cavernous lockers.</span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >The cabin entrance with sliding hatch and wash-boards has a sill at seat level. The deck is swept-laid in teak over a ply sub deck. The wide teak laid side decks with grab rails on the coach-roof deck afford easy and clear passage forward to a clear and totally uncluttered fore deck. Twin Sampson posts take the heel of the bowsprit and forward mooring lines. Right up forward the deck drops to a well to take the anchor and chain.</span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >The rig is set up with halyards led aft along the coach-roof deck through clutches to a top-action Harken 9 winch each side of the entrance hatch. Jib and staysail sheets are led through lead blocks on deck tracks to jammers</span></p> <p >There are two cabin ventilators on <span class=SpellE>dorade</span> boxes on the coach-roof deck.</span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><u><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >Accommodation </span></u></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >Three berths in two cabins. This is deceptively spacious for the size of the yacht, comfortable seating, all varnished joinery, inlaid cabin sole lifts in panels. Several cast iron ballast blocks are secured in the bilge below</span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >Fore cabin with single berth to stbd. The feet of the berth reach forward under the deck chain well. There is a porta-<span class=SpellE>potti</span> to port</span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >Saloon cabin. Port and starboard settee berths.  Shaped, buttoned cushions. Shaped bunk boards. Exposed varnished yacht sides.  Fiddle shelf above each bunk.</span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >Fold down chart table against the after bulkhead to starboard with red led lamp and switch panel</span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >Plumbed in sink with pop-up whale tap. Tap folds down to allow cooker to slide across. A 2-burner Origo spirit stove mounted on rails on the bulkhead over the end of the port berth slides across to the centre-line against the companionway steps to use bunk. Storage for pans and food under bunk</span></p> <u><span mso-ansi-language:EN-GB;mso-fareast-language:EN-US; mso-bidi-language:AR-SA'><br clear=all style='mso-special-character:line-break; page-break-before:always'> </span></u> <p class=MsoNormal><u><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; ><o:p><span style='text-decoration:none'>&nbsp;</span></o:p></span></u></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><u><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >Since purchased in 2015 works carried out include</span></u></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >Antifoul blasted off and hull, sheer strakes and centreboard repainted 2016</span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >Strakes, capping rail cabin sides hatches and washboard stripped and finished with <span class=SpellE>Sikkens</span>. 2018</span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >New mast, boom, gaff and bowsprit supplied by Freeland yacht spars 2016</span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >New stainless-steel fittings supplied by Classic Marine Woodbridge. 2016</span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >New stainless-steel standing rigging supplied and fitted Quay Rigging Poole 2016</span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >New running rigging – <span class=SpellE>Liros</span> <span class=SpellE>hempline</span> from Jimmy Green 2016</span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >LED lighting in cabin, sump pump for sink 2017</span></p> <p margin-left:3.6pt;vertical-align:baseline'><span style='font-size:12.0pt; font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; >All sails cleaned, checked and repaired Quay Sails Poole 2015 </span></p> <p style='margin-bottom:10.0pt;line-height:115%'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif; mso-ansi-language: EN-GB'>Sail Inventory for Patience </span></p> <table class=MsoTableGrid border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=616 style='width:462.0pt;border-collapse:collapse;border:none;mso-border-alt:solid windowtext .5pt; mso-yfti-tbllook:1184;mso-padding-alt:0cm 5.4pt 0cm 5.4pt'> <tr style='mso-yfti-irow:0;mso-yfti-firstrow:yes'> <td width=215 valign=top style='width:161.35pt;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt; > <p >Sail</span></p> </td> <td width=85 valign=top style='width:63.8pt;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt; border-left:none;mso-border-left-alt:solid windowtext .5pt;mso-border-alt: solid windowtext .5pt;padding:0cm 5.4pt 0cm 5.4pt'> <p >Area <span class=SpellE>sq</span> ft</span></p> </td> <td width=85 valign=top style='width:63.75pt;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt; border-left:none;mso-border-left-alt:solid windowtext .5pt;mso-border-alt: solid windowtext .5pt;padding:0cm 5.4pt 0cm 5.4pt'> <p >Area m2</span></p> </td> <td width=77 valign=top style='width:57.55pt;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt; border-left:none;mso-border-left-alt:solid windowtext .5pt;mso-border-alt: solid windowtext .5pt;padding:0cm 5.4pt 0cm 5.4pt'> <p >Colour</span></p> </td> <td width=154 valign=top style='width:115.55pt;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt; border-left:none;mso-border-left-alt:solid windowtext .5pt;mso-border-alt: solid windowtext .5pt;padding:0cm 5.4pt 0cm 5.4pt'> <p >Hanks 